instruction: [INST] Analyze this file to learn MacBook motherboard repair. The 'definitions' section explains key technical terms. The 'threads' section contains real-world repair discussions. Use both sections to understand and learn how to troubleshoot MacBook issues. Posts from username 'larossmann' , 'dukefawks' , and '2informaticos' are posts from trusted experts.[/INST]

definitions.820-02098: What is 820-02098? a LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER.
definitions.PP3V3_S2: What is PP3V3_S2? PP3V3_S2 is a typo of PP3V3_S3.
definitions.A2442: What is A2442? A2442 is a model number for a 14 inch size MacBook Pro Retina from years Late 2021 M1 with EMC 3650, that may contain one of these boards depending on the year & configuration: 820-02098..
definitions.A2485: What is A2485? A2485 is a model number for a 16 inch size MacBook Pro Retina from years Late 2021 M1 with EMC 3651, that may contain one of these boards depending on the year & configuration: 820-02100, 820-02382..

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-02098</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER> water damage, no <SIGNAL>PP5V_S2_MAIN</SIGNAL>
threads.message: Hello , first of all I'd like to say that this is my firt board level repair so please be patient if I get things wrong (like I forget to specify important details), I'll try my best. I've got a <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-02098</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER> board which is liquid damaged. Firt of all after removing the board i checked for liquid damage and I cleaned it as much as i could with IPA, but averall the board looked pretty good (no visibly broken componets, no blacked-out areas).  I then moved to check if the capacitors with the most oxidation where shorted out but I couldn't find any. Luckily I got my hands on the schematics ([URL]https://www.badcaps.net/forum/showthread.php?t=110182&highlight=m1+pro+schematic[/URL]), with that plus the repair wiki i found out that my 3.8V line is working properly (or at least I read 3.8V according to the repair wiki). The problem comes with the <SIGNAL>PP5V_S2_MAIN</SIGNAL> line, indeed I don't get any voltage (measured from the inductor indicated in trw), so I moved to the boardview and found that that inductor is connected to 3 pads of the adiacent chip (the one in the image, the pads highlighted). My issue is that that area wasn't damaged at all by liquid (at least not visibly) so I don't know why the problem could be there, but also it looks like the pads aren't properly soldered. I decided to try and desolder it using aboundant flux and a hot-air station. At first I set it to 200C but couldn't get anything moving so I moved gradually to 300C until I decided to stop because I didn't want to cause any damage. My questions are: could this chip be the problem or maybe the absence of <SIGNAL>PP5V_S2_MAIN</SIGNAL> is determined by some other component I couldn't locate? If so how can remove it properly?

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-02098</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER> water damage, no <SIGNAL>PP5V_S2_MAIN</SIGNAL>
threads.message:
First of all, welcome to the forum!

Keep in mind, the temp set on the hot air station, is not the expected temp on the board.
You will probably need to set 400-450 degrees on the hot air station.
Also need to adjust air flow properly; practice on scrap boards.

When you deal with a power supply controller, check first if the chip gets correct voltage on its power pins; 10-12 in this case.
It also need an enable signal, <SIGNAL>P5VS2TPS_PWR_EN</SIGNAL>.

Do you get other voltages on <CHIP>U7700</CHIP> and <CHIP>U8100</CHIP>?
What about <SIGNAL>3V3_S2</SIGNAL> and <SIGNAL>1V2_S2</SIGNAL>?
Is the machine recognized in DFU mode?

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-02098</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER> water damage, no <SIGNAL>PP5V_S2_MAIN</SIGNAL>
threads.message:
Lot of small coils around <CHIP>U7700</CHIP> and <CHIP>U8100</CHIP>.
Some of them must get voltage, in order to enter DFU.

Be aware, many coils are tied together.
Use the common output pin of one coil to check; don't waste time measuring on each common coil.

Both chips have also several LDO voltages to check; look at pages 37 & 41.

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-02098</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER> water damage, no <SIGNAL>PP5V_S2_MAIN</SIGNAL>
threads.message:
Page 37 and 41 of schematic, show you the LDO voltages of mentioned chips: LDOS blocks on the bottom.
On the left side you can see the input voltage of any LDO (output on the right).
If an input voltage is not present, output LDO will not be present, of course.
Any LDO generated from <SIGNAL>3V8_AON</SIGNAL>, must be present.

<CHIP>U7700</CHIP> and <CHIP>U8100</CHIP> have also many buck controllers, which also must work before the board starts.

You should check which voltage is generated, or not.
In case not, check for short there.

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-02098</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER> water damage, no <SIGNAL>PP5V_S2_MAIN</SIGNAL>
threads.message:
Any point of a missing voltage rail is good to check.
I hope you can find one with easy access.
Don't make any short more with multimeter probes; get ones with fine tips.

<SIGNAL>1V8_S2</SIGNAL> comes out from L7830.
<SIGNAL>1V2_S2</SIGNAL> comes out from L8280.
All S2 and AWAKE voltages must be present, to assist M1 in power on sequence.

As you get <SIGNAL>3V8_AON</SIGNAL>, check if Master (<CHIP>U8100</CHIP>) LDOs derivated from <SIGNAL>3V8_AON</SIGNAL> are present (page 41).

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-02098</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER> water damage, no <SIGNAL>PP5V_S2_MAIN</SIGNAL>
threads.message:
If is same model, is the same platfom, so you can change it.
<CHIP>U8100</CHIP> is master PMU and must generate <SIGNAL>3V3_S2</SIGNAL> by itself, without an external control.
It only needs <SIGNAL>3V8_AON</SIGNAL> to generate 1V2/1V8__AON and <SIGNAL>3V3_S2</SIGNAL>.
Also generates <SIGNAL>1V5_AON</SIGNAL> for its core and 1V8 for SRAM.

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-02098</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER> water damage, no <SIGNAL>PP5V_S2_MAIN</SIGNAL>
threads.message:
If 1V2/<SIGNAL>1V8_AON</SIGNAL> are both present, <SIGNAL>PP3V8_AON_MPMU_ISNS</SIGNAL> is surely present.
Then <SIGNAL>3V3_S2</SIGNAL> must be there too; unless is shorted to ground, or has lower resistance than normal.
Possibly bad solders.
In fact, all LDOs derived from <SIGNAL>PP3V8_AON_MPMU_ISNS</SIGNAL>, should be there.
